DESCRIPTION
Hardening audit finding (med; highest-value hardening gap). capture-run already confines artifact paths via resolveArtifactPath (realpath/EvalSymlinks, etude-094) but the same class is UNGUARDED elsewhere: (1) capture --output/--input addFileArtifact (capture.go:252) and capture-gate raw_output.path buildSeatResult (capture.go:544) os.ReadFile ANY absolute path, following symlinks -> a machine-fed gate JSON could exfiltrate e.g. /etc/passwd into a stored artifact; (2) replay --output (replay.go:215) os.WriteFile through a symlink with no Lstat/regular-file guard (the runner-output READ at exec_runner.go:129 is Lstat-guarded; the write-out is not). Apply the capture-run-style confinement/regular-file checks. Severity is med IF gate files are ever machine/PR-derived, low if always hand-authored.

DESIGN
RECOMMENDATION: SCOPED BUILD

IN scope (2 sites):
  - capture-gate raw_output.path (capture.go:544, buildSeatResult os.ReadFile) — the
    one real (latent) untrusted-input vector: the gate JSON is the realistic
    machine-fed surface (CI/PR automation may emit it). Apply a regular-file +
    no-symlink read guard (NOT the capture-run relative-to-dir model — see rationale).
  - replay --output (replay.go:220, os.WriteFile) — direct user arg, but a WRITE that
    follows symlinks could clobber an unexpected target. Cheap defensive-depth
    no-symlink-follow write guard mirroring exec_runner's existing output guard.

OUT of scope (1 site), excluded by threat model:
  - capture --input / --output (capture.go:252, addFileArtifact os.ReadFile). These
    paths come DIRECTLY from CLI flags the user types (`--input role=path`,
    `--output role=path`). A trusting local user who types a path can already read any
    file they own; there is NO natural confinement boundary for a bare CLI arg (unlike
    capture-run, whose paths are anchored to the spec DIRECTORY). Confining these would
    BREAK the legitimate use of capturing a file from anywhere the user chooses, and
    would buy no security under the current all-hand-authored trust model. Do NOT touch.

## Strongest reason to build (vs DEFER)
capture-gate is the one site whose input shape (a JSON document with an embedded file
path) is plausibly machine/CI-emitted rather than hand-typed — that is exactly the
"machine-fed gate JSON names /etc/passwd and exfiltrates it into a stored, content-
addressed, possibly-pushed artifact" vector the audit flagged as med. The guard is
small, won't break any current usage (no existing test or doc example sets
raw_output.path to a symlink), and closes the highest-value gap. replay --output rides
along as a near-free write-side guard that matches a guard the runner-output READ path
already has (consistency, not new behavior). The direct-CLI reads are correctly left
unconfined.

## Per-site threat verdict
  - capture-gate raw_output.path: REAL (latent). Untrusted-input story holds the moment
    a gate file is produced by automation rather than hand-authored. Worth hardening now;
    cheap and non-breaking.
  - replay --output: LOW but cheap. User named the path, so not an exfiltration vector,
    but a symlinked --output silently clobbering another file is a real footgun; the
    READ side is already guarded, so guarding the WRITE side is consistency + defensive
    depth.
  - capture --input/--output: NO BOUNDARY. Direct user-typed args with no anchor;
    confinement is the wrong move (breaks legitimate use, secures nothing under the
    current trust model). Explicitly excluded.

## Confinement model decision for capture-gate (the non-obvious call)
Do NOT reuse capture-run's resolveArtifactPath relative-to-spec-dir model here. Reasons:
  1. No stable anchor. --gate-file accepts "-" (stdin); gate JSON can be piped from a
     pipeline with no on-disk directory, so "relative to the gate-file's directory" is
     undefined for the stdin case. capture-run always has a real spec file on disk.
  2. The gate file is a thin RECORD-of-an-attempt, not a portable bundle. capture-run
     spec dirs are deliberately self-contained/portable (artifacts shipped alongside the
     spec); gate raw_output transcripts are not bundled that way today, and forcing
     relative-to-dir would change the path contract AND break stdin.
Chosen guard for raw_output.path: a regular-file + no-symlink Lstat guard (same shape as
exec_runner.go:164-173). This blocks the symlink-follow exfiltration (the actual attack:
a symlink named in the JSON pointing at /etc/passwd) while leaving the path itself
otherwise as-is, so legitimate absolute or cwd-relative transcript paths keep working and
stdin keeps working. This is the lighter, correct guard — it neutralizes the symlink
vector without imposing a containment boundary that has no natural anchor here.

## The guards (exact shape — design only, no code)
Add one shared helper in internal/cli (e.g. readRegularFile(path) ([]byte, error)) that:
  - os.Lstat(path); if not exist -> wrap as a plain "does not exist" / read error (a
    missing transcript is a user typo, not an escape — mirror resolveArtifactPath's
    ErrNotExist handling tone).
  - if fi.Mode()&os.ModeSymlink != 0 (or !fi.Mode().IsRegular()) -> reject with a clear
    "raw_output %s must be a regular file (not a symlink)" style error.
  - else os.ReadFile(path) and return.
Site wiring:
  - capture.go:544 buildSeatResult: replace os.ReadFile(s.RawOutput.Path) with the
    regular-file-guarded read; keep the existing "read raw_output %s: %w" wrap.
  - replay.go:220 write-out: before os.WriteFile(outputPath, ...), Lstat outputPath; if
    it EXISTS and is a symlink or non-regular file, reject ("refusing to write --output
    %s: not a regular file"). If it does not exist, proceed (normal create). Open with
    O_CREATE|O_WRONLY|O_TRUNC|O_NOFOLLOW via os.OpenFile to also defeat the create-time
    TOCTOU/symlink-follow on the final path component, then write res.Output and chmod/
    perm 0o644 (preserve current mode). Keep "write output file: %w" wrap.
NOTE: do NOT entangle with refactor bead etude-6j8 (moving inferMediaType to
artifactstore). resolveArtifactPath stays in capture_run.go untouched (we are not reusing
it). The new guard helper is independent and small.

